In my new book (not out yet), Picture Perfect Flash, published by @rocky_nook, I'm talking about a technique where you bounced a light-colored gel into a white background and let the bounce colored-light create a painterly effect on your subject's skin. It takes an otherwise ordinary photo with a plain white background and turns it into something special you want to hang as a piece of art. So fun! Would you consider trying this, or is it not your jam? Model: @reneemurden taken with the @canonusa R5 and a @profoto B1 strobe. #colorgels #creativeheadshots #studiophotography #pictureperfectflash #lightingtechniques #creativeportraits #profoto #canonr5 #canonexploreroflight

In my new book Picture Perfect Flash (Available for pre-order on Amazon), I talk about the huge impact architecture can have as makeshift light modifiers. For this photo, we bounced a @canonusa EL-1 flash towards the cement beam opposite of @ivanduranphoto to create this awesome portrait of him! Lighting with a flash doesn't mean, you have to point it at the person, you can make the light much larger and softer if you can bounce it off flat surfaces like this. The results are incredible and I love them! What do you guys think? Cool right? Please help me congratulate @ivanduranphoto for getting hitched!

Photo by me of @missusa R’Bonney.  Sending love and positive vibes today to @rbonneynola as she takes on @missuniverse tonight! Wish her luck guys! She is the bestest ever! @missusa.

Straight out of Camera. Multiple exposure with @canonusa R5, dragged shutter, light painting, and motion blur all working together to create the illusion that the couple is inside or behind the background not in front of it. Shot during my class in Kuala Lumpur. Three flashes @canonusa EL-1, Canon R5, RF 70-200 mm. F/2.8. One flash is behind her on the table, the flash on my camera is the fill, and a third flash in front of her to contour her face.  The third flash in front of her face is key IMO.

I am amazed at the incredible detail that can be achieved with the new @canonusa RF 100-300 f/2.8. This photo required some tricky lighting. We used a @profoto B1 pointed at the roof to separate the black flag in the background and the black hat Gary is wearing with a bit of rim light. Next, we used a @profoto magnum reflector to provide very hard light to his face to achieve that awesome contrast. Lastly, we had to put a paper towel on the bottom half of the modifier to avoid light from hitting the leather jacket and to avoid hotpots on the shiny leather. If you want to see some BTS for this photo, I posted a video on my Youtube channel about it. Last one from this series during the @bhphoto BILD Expo at the @canonusa 1970’s booth.  The technique here was to use short lighting during a one second dragged exposure.  It’s rare to see short lighting with this technique, but for this example it gave the photo structure and most importantly, the lighting had believability. Meaning, it looks like she was on an actual dance floor and was lit by the club lights.  Instead of just looking like studio photography lights.

In-Camera Skin Softening Technique.  One of my favorite techniques to create some special and people love it! It takes some practice, and you do need a very strong strobe. At least 500 watts modified to focus the beam and output even more power.  You need to move the camera and the subject with perfect timing. The results are absolutely beautiful! I teach this technique in my new @rocky_nook book titled Picture Perfect Flash.  Would you try this? Let me know. ☺️
